New Rules for the World Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let us assume that the world's leading politicians would once again convene in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new world economic order.
Naturally, they would primarily address today's issues: the eurozone crisis, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. But dealing with these questions would force the assembled leaders to go beyond and reconsider the overall solidity of worldwide economic arrangements.
Here are seven principles based on sound common sense for global economic steering that they might agree upon.
(I discuss these in more detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. The markets must be deeply embedded in existing governance systems.
The notion that markets can regulate themselves suffered a mortal blow in the recent financial crisis and should be buried once and for all.
Markets need other societal institutions to support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies to set and enforce rules.
They depend on stabilization functions provided by central banks and counter-cyclical fiscal policy.
They require the political acceptance brought about by progressive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all of this applies equally to global markets.
2. In the foreseeable future, democratic state leadership is likely to be largely organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives on, even if it may have weakened somewhat, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile endeavor.
<s>Dass die nationalen Regierungen erhebliche Kontrollgewalt an die transnationalen Institutionen abgeben, ist kaum zu erwarten; zudem würde eine Regelharmonisierung Gesellschaften mit unterschiedlichen Bedürfnissen und Präferenzen nichts nutzen.
<s>Die Europäische Union könnte die einzige Ausnahme von diesem Axiom sein, obwohl ihre gegenwärtige Krise es eher zu belegen scheint.
<s>Allzu oft verschwenden wir internationale Zusammenarbeit auf übertrieben ehrgeizige Ziele. Dabei kommen letztlich schwache Ergebnisse heraus, die den kleinsten gemeinsamen Nenner zwischen den großen Ländern darstellen.
<s>Wenn internationale Zusammenarbeit „erfolgreich“ ist, bringt sie Regeln hervor, die entweder zahnlos sind oder die Präferenzen der mächtigeren Länder widerspiegeln.
<s>Die Baseler Regeln über die Kapitalanforderungen und die Regeln der Welthandelsorganisation zu Subventionen, geistigem Eigentum und Investitionsmaßnahmen typisieren diese Art von übertriebenem Ehrgeiz.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic processes at home instead of undermining them.

3. Pluralistischer Wohlstand: The admission that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built on the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best meet their needs.
The U.S., Europe, and Japan have produced comparably high levels of wealth over the long term.
However, their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social security, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these “models” – each one different in every decade – will then be presented as the great success that one should emulate.
<s>Die erfolgreichsten Gesellschaften der Zukunft werden Raum für Experimente lassen und eine weitere Evolution ihrer Institutionen zulassen.
<s>Eine Weltwirtschaft, die die Notwendigkeit und den Wert institutioneller Vielfalt anerkennt, wird eine derartige Experimentierfreudigkeit und evolutionäre Entwicklung eher fördern als unterdrücken.
<s>4. Länder haben das Recht, ihre eigenen Regeln und Institutionen zu schützen.
<s>Die vorgenannten Grundsätze mögen unverfänglich erscheinen.
<s>Aber sie tragen mächtige Implikationen in sich, die mit der vorherrschenden Meinung der Globalisierungsbefürworter kollidieren.
A corresponding implication is that individual countries have the right to protect their national institutional decisions.
Recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the tools to shape and preserve their own institutions – in other words, to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries can retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect consumer health and safety – and that they should be allowed to do so, potentially erecting barriers at their borders if trade is demonstrably threatening indigenous practices that enjoy broad public support.
If proponents of globalization are correct, demands for such protection measures without evidence or support will fail.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve so that competing values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of retaining national regulations – can both be adequately heard in public debates.
5. Länder haben kein Recht, anderen ihre eigenen Institutionen aufzuzwingen.
Der Einsatz von Restriktionen beim grenzüberschreitenden Handel oder im Finanzbereich zur Beibehaltung von Werten und Regeln im eigenen Land ist nicht mit ihrem Einsatz zu verwechseln, um anderen Ländern diese Werte und Regeln aufzuzwingen.
Die Regeln der Globalisierung sollten Amerikaner oder Europäer nicht zum Konsum von Waren zwingen, die auf eine Weise produziert werden, die die meisten Bürger in diesen Ländern unakzeptabel finden.
Genauso wenig aber sollten sie den USA oder der EU ermöglichen, Handelssanktionen oder sonstige Druckmittel einzusetzen, um Arbeitsmarktregeln, Umweltpolitik oder Finanzregulierung anderer Länder zu ändern.
Länder haben ein Recht auf Unterschiedlichkeit, nicht auf erzwungene Konvergenz.

<s>6. International agreements for regulating interactions between national institutions: Relying on national states to provide the basic governance functions of the world economy does not mean we should forego international rules.
The Bretton Woods system, for example, had clear rules, albeit limited in scope and depth.
A complete free-for-all would benefit no one.
We need traffic rules for the world economy that help vehicles of different sizes, shapes, and speeds to navigate around each other, rather than prescribing identical cars or uniform speed limits.
<s>We should strive for a maximum of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot be granted the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives these principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultations – where these actually take place, within the national states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
Then we can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
For undemocratic states, therefore, less liberal rules must apply.
This is the set of principles that architects of the next world economic order must accept.
Most importantly, they must accept the ultimate paradox that each of these principles illustrates: Globalization works best when you don't push it too far.
